lets goo

Orb: On the Movements of Earth. 10/10

Funniest one to finish first, as like, good chance this is one of the shows of the year lmfao, what a fucking great anime. The opening did not leave my head at any point during the shows run, i was chomping at the bit for the full release.

(and god what a good song)

The twists and turns orb takes you through is comparable to a few other shows that span a similar amount of time, but i don't think i've seen it executed as well here as it has in anything else, everything is so tightly packed and interwoven-

- which makes some of the later end reveals so fucking cool. The boarding and direction of the whole thing is consistently great, with a couple standout episodes that make what is like, just people talking like, feel so big and powerful, like ough, great stuff, easily a 10/10

Sorairo Utility. 10/10

Godddd what a cute and heartfelt and wholesome show and aaagghhh god. I was really struggling to decide if i wanted to give this a 9 or a 10 but ultimately anything that can make me smile for it's whole runtime *and* almost get me crying is worth a 10.

Like, i enjoy my silly cute girls doing cute things shows, learn about a hobby while these fun designs do dumb stuff and all that. But like, god there's a whole additional level to this that just really hit me good. 
The quiet, small moments that break both the show's character-

- and the characters themselves and let you like, get a peek behind the curtain, they're just, man. The final episode being so focused on that and like, almost melancholic while having some of the goofiest boards and direction,,, man i love it, i hope we see more of those girls.

Throughout the federal election campaign, I am going to be looking at elections from Canada's past. 
Today, we are starting things off with the very first election in Canadian history: 1867!
Voting lasted two months, there were riots, corruption and more!

üßµ1/10

When Canadian Confederation happened on July 1, 1867, Governor General Charles Monck appointed Sir John A. Macdonald as Canada's first Prime Minister.
But, an election still had to happen.
Canada's first election would begin over a month later and last for weeks.

üßµ2/10

At the time, three parties were taking part in the election: The Conservatives, the Liberals and the Anti-Confederation Party.
Macdonald led the Conservatives, but the Liberals had no official leader. Joseph Howe led the Anti-Confederation Party.

üßµ3/10

The election took place over a six week period from Aug. 7 to Sept. 20, with polls closing at different dates. 
To vote, a person had to be 21 years of age or older, a British subject and male. Women, government employees and First Nations were not allowed to vote.

üßµ4/10

To vote in Ontario, Quebec and Nova Scotia, a person had to publicly declare their choice. This allowed for corruption to run rampant as people were coerced by employers to vote a certain way.
New Brunswick had used the secret ballot since 1855.

üßµ5/10

Since polls opened at different times, the Conservative government opened polls it knew it could win quickly first, then gradually opened polling in tougher districts in the hopes that early Conservative victories would sway voters in tougher areas.

üßµ6/10

In the Kamouraska District, a riot broke out on nomination day when all candidates were proposed at a single meeting. The returning officer had to take refuge from the rioters. No nominations happened and no one from the district was elected to Parliament until 1869.

üßµ7/10

While only 11% of the total population of Canada at the time could legally vote, eligible voter turnout was 74.3%.
Sir John A. Macdonald and the Conservatives won the election with 100 seats. 
The Liberals won 62 seats and served as the Official Opposition. 

üßµ8/10

The Anti-Confederation Party won 18 seats, all in Nova Scotia.
After Britain refused to allow Nova Scotia to secede, 11 of the Anti-Confederation MPs moved over to the Conservatives.

i've been liveposting my struggles with game development, but i'm not even sure if i ever gave you guys context on what i'm doing

so, let me explain

a couple of weeks (months?) ago, while talking with folks on stream, i said something along the lines of "wouldn't it be funny if i made a game?"

and as I surround myself with enablers (lovingly), i shouldn't be surprised that they said 
"i bet it would be dope"

and such, my self-inflicted struggle began

however, i knew that it would be stuck in creative limbo if i didn't have a deadline, and i thought to myself:
"surely, three months is enough time to make a game!"

i mean people do make games in less than that during game jams
disregard the fact that usually they know what they're doing üôÉ

ANYWAY that is how i decided on a date - i usually celebrate my birthday on stream, so it would be a perfect opportunity to make a WORLD PREMIERE of my very first game! 

BUT! as time went on, i realized that i need to put down very strict limitations on what i want to implement in game

the more i learned about Ren'Py, the more i wanted to do, and my project grew
I have now SO MANY IDEAS i want to implement
but i have a deadline! i won't be able to implement all of that!

so cuts were made
and final decision that regardless of the state, i will release my game on my birthday stream

technically, my game IS playable!
I could release it even now!

But i want to push myself to squeeze as much as i can, so what I show in my birthday stream on the 5th of April is the best it can be at the moment!

Okay, actually explaining the game is a bit wordy but also skipping any of it just makes me waffle elsewhere so strap in for a full run-down:
The game is called Contact. One person plays against the rest of the crowd. They think of a word the rest needs to guess and confine the game to one topic.

To gain information, the other players can force hints in the form of letters (provided in order, one by one) through the core part of gameplay. Any player can come up with a word from the defined topic, then prompt it with a word or simple phrase. Any other player thinking they know the word [...]

[...] can then call out "contact" to start the one initiating counting down from ten. At the end of the countdown both say the word they were thinking of and if it's the same, the next letter needs to be revealed. The word giver can oppose this by trying to guess the word themselves [...]

[...] during the countdown. They can throw in as many words as they like, and if they say the correct one, the countdown stops (and the word is banned). So it's about having prompts that are clear enough for someone in the crowd to guess, but unclear enough so the word giver can't. It's fun. Imo.

I'm revisiting Skowronek's contribution to the JER special issue on the early US state that @gauthamrao.bsky.social and I did a few years ago, and I'm increasingly sympathetic to his frustration with us historians. His basic complaint...

is that we've stopped studying historical development and instead keep focusing on historical continuities. So all the work showing a robust early US state amounts to fact-checking right wing talking points instead of explaining how we got to where we are. More fundamentally...

this is an example of the wider abandonment of the project of "discovering" historical "laws." Some Marxist historians are an exception, but to my mind they mostly elaborate endless epiphenomena on the same underlying Marxist model that I find inadequate in many ways...

I think Polanyi's "double movement" and Kalecki's "political business cycle" offer promising theoretical orientations, and ofc there's everything we've learned about race and gender making, but I think we are still lacking a lot of needed concepts just to begin formulating the right questions. /fin

If Delicate wasn't made, Anti Hero is probably the song i'd stan the most. I listened to this song at BC Place for a sporting event in 2023, who knew that a full year later Swift would play the song in the same building? Weird how life can be like that

But when I did listen to the song, man did it hit me more than it should. It made me realise any past decision or action that i've made wasn't a reflection of who I am as a person (sadly that part came back 2 weeks ago), and through that lyric alone I tried my best to change things to be better

From that point, I did succeed in this, Whether it'd be losing weight, changing the way i think, or anything else, It was through the power of this song. "Always Older but Never Wiser" is also reminiscing on my personality before this song too because of certain thing i'd say or do that affected

things in the past that i've come to realise and some of them I regret. I've often not had good sleeps because of these realisations (Midnights become my afternoons), so I've often changed my sleep schedule to fit my new lifestyle. It's safe to assume that this song changed and still is changing me
and I was happy to listen to this song when I got around to this album. üíô

Is generalized epilepsy a seizure of the whole brain or a specific brain network? 

In our new paper out now in @naturecomms.bsky.social, we investigate this by combining brain abnormalities and DBS with the human connectome. 

Paper: nature.com/articles/s41... 

A üßµ below:
Patients with idiopathic generalized epilepsy (IGE) typically present with generalized spike wave discharges with 'normal' brain MRI, leaving the neuroanatomical basis of IGE unclear.

However, the ENIGMA study by Whelan et al. and previous large neuroimaging studies in IGE have shown that subtle brain abnormalities can be detected compared to a healthy person's brain.

academic.oup.com/brain/articl...

We believed these brain abnormalities could give us crucial clues about where the generalized seizure starts or travels to in the brain. Think of pebbles that track a path the generalized seizure prefers to travel along...
We therefore collected all published coordinates of voxel-wise brain abnormalities associated with IGE and plotted them here:

These brain abnormalities are scattered throughout the brain and, while the thalamus is the most consistently involved region in line with the ENIGMA study, only 17% of the coordinates fall within the thalamus. Could a wider brain network be involved?

We therefore computed the network connections of these brain abnormalities using the human connectome and identified an 'IGE network' involving the SMA, perirolandic cortex, thalamus, piriform cortex, frontal poles, superior temporal gyrus, precuneus, and cerebellum.

This IGE network encompassed the regions identified in the ENIGMA study and was further validated by data from EEG-fMRI studies that show BOLD activation at the time of the generalized spike-wave in the positive functional connections of the IGE network.
While it was encouraging to see the IGE network align with previous findings in IGE patients, something else quickly caught our eye...

We saw an interleaved pattern over the motor cortex, which reminded us of 
@ndosenbach.bsky.social 's inter-effector regions and somatocognitive action network (SCAN). Could the IGE network share connections with the SCAN?

YES! The IGE network beautifully aligned with the inter-effector regions and SCAN which is an evolutionary preserved integrated action and executive control system to coordinate gross movements, control muscle groups, posture, and internal physiology.

My take: generalized seizures may 'hijack' (parts of) the SCAN resulting in the electroclinical expression of generalized seizures along intrinsic human brain networks leading to convulsions of the whole body or myoclonic jerks as well as loss of consciousness or absences.

Digging deeper we found a thalamic peak of the IGE network in the centromedian nucleus of the thalamus, which is exactly the region where neurosurgeons place their DBS electrodes to treat generalized seizures!

We collected all published and unpublished IGE cases we could get our hands on (thank you collaborators!) and we found the leads nicely aligned with the peak in the IGE network. Patients had a median response rate of 90% (!), supporting the CM as an off label DBS target for generalized seizures.

The thalamic peak in our IGE network even converged on the same MNI coordinate as a recently identified DBS sweet-spot for IGE, potentially suggesting an optimal DBS target based on connectivity of brain abnormalities in IGE.

We then combined the networks of brain abnormalities in IGE with the CM DBS data and identified a convergent IGE network, which could represent a brain stimulation target to better control generalized seizures.

Huge thank you to first author Gongjun Ji for leading this study, to @foxmdphd.bsky.social for his invaluable mentorship at @braincircuits.bsky.social, and all collaborators for their support and generous sharing of their data:

There's something to be said, especially for kids, for seeing oneself in a character, at least as a jumping-on point.
My daughter cares not a whip for most superhero stuff, nor a lot of anime...but she likes Wonder Woman and My Hero Academia, because WW is a girl and MHA has young girl characters...

...my son loves MHA because he sees himself in Midoriya...and he LOVES Miles Morales because he's similarly young.

I think for Spider-Man (Peter Parker) he's always been depicted as "just a young dumb kid", even when he was holding down part time jobs and going to college, he was never treated...

...with an adult-level of respect, and kids identify with things like that.

People naturally TEND to gravitate towards characters they can relate to and understand. It's a human condition that you can empathize more with people you understand.

Not requiring that is an exception, not a rule...

Two new preprints from my group at WashU!

First, Merve @mileritayar.bsky.social tests whether people place an effort cost on switching between cognitive control settings. We find that people avoid switching between focused and relaxed attentional states.

osf.io/preprints/os...

People trade off this cost with interference demands! They become more likely to choose lists of more incongruent Stroop trials if this minimizes switches between attentional states. This work nicely complements the work on "reconfiguration costs" by Ivan Grahek from the @shenhavlab.bsky.social.

Second, Cathy @cathyzhang.bsky.social has developed a new framework to infer mind wandering (lapses of attention) from behavior. She combines the GLM-HMMs  from @jpillowtime.bsky.social's group with a parametric version of the Sustained Attention to Response Task (SART).

osf.io/preprints/ps...

This way, she gets a time series of model-predicted attentional states for each participant. These states predict a variety of independent behavioral patterns, including speeding up of RTs under mind wandering, self-reported task-unrelated thoughts, and a shift towards these thoughts across time.
